items.title: Jalmenus evagoras evagoras
items.content_text: Adults, caterpillars and pupae on a 2m tall Acacia melanoxylon (Blackwood). Not far from observation 8007. Apparently unusual to see melanoxylon being used as a host in Vic.

items.title: Hesperilla donnysa donnysa
items.content_text: New species record for Riddells Creek. 1st pic shows it on stem of its host plant, Gahnia radula, which surrounds an unspoilt Billabong. I saw lots possibly emerging from the base of plants.

items.title: Pseudalmenus chlorinda zephyrus
items.content_text: Flying around and landing on a few young bipinnate wattles (Acacia mearnsii and dealbata). Only one adult seen. Some of the A. mearnsii plants here seem to be suffering from Fireblight beetle attack.

items.title: Candalides hyacinthina hyacinthina
items.content_text: On Pultenaea mollis.

items.title: Zizina labradus labradus
items.content_text: On garden-planted Pultenaea daphnoides. At least two individuals pictured here.

items.title: Lampides boeticus
items.content_text: On garden-planted Pultenaea daphnoides. This plant species is locally indigenous to the area although this is a locally-sourced, garden-planted specimen. Two individuals photographed.

items.title: Junonia villida calybe
items.content_text: Not recorded flying in Melbourne in June (KDunn). Bright sunny day. First day of Winter.

items.title: Vanessa itea
items.content_text: Feeding on garden-planted Banksia integrifolia.

items.title: Eurema smilax smilax
items.content_text: Flying around garden-planted banksias, didn't land. Photo taken in flight but very poor quality so not uploaded here - good enough for ID.

items.title: Eurema smilax smilax, Oxalis spp.
items.content_text: This species is a vagrant, rarely seen in Victoria. Feeding on oxalis (possibly O.perennans) on a weedy/grassy/mown roadside next to a horse paddock. Flew to many oxalis flowers and the occasional Hypochoeris radicata.

items.title: Eurema smilax smilax
items.content_text: Flying around backyard, seen by a few people but didn't land for a photo. Rarely seen in Vic and doesn't breed here.

items.title: Vanessa itea
items.content_text: Three wing positions. Two individuals photographed. Last pic feeding in garden planted Banksia marginata. Camera flash brightens up pics - it looks almost black in some light/angles.

items.title: Heteronympha penelope penelope
items.content_text: Probably 3 individuals pictured. Occasional H.penelope among 1000s of common browns. Similar to male common brown (but no male common brown fly this time of year) and slightly smaller than female common brown. New species record for Riddells Creek.

items.title: Heteronympha merope merope
items.content_text: Thousands flying now and for the past 2-3 weeks - all females.

items.title: Heteronympha penelope penelope
items.content_text: Thousands of female Common Browns at this time of year and maybe 1 in 100 is H. penelope. Very difficult to find unless looking hard for them. Looks similar to male Common Browns which have all died by now. New species record for Riddells Creek.

items.title: Geitoneura acantha
items.content_text: Occasional individuals seen flying among the thousands of Common Browns. Easy to spot as they are much smaller and a lighter brown.

items.title: Delias harpalyce
items.content_text: Lots around forested area over the past couple of weeks. Regularly feeding on garden planted banksias (marginata on this occasion).

items.title: Heteronympha merope merope
items.content_text: Hundreds feeding on the sap of a sick old Acacia mearnsii trunk. All females. One Klugs Xenica there too. Next day the numbers were only a few dozen at a time with Red Wattlebird grasping the vertical trunk and picking them off as they landed.

items.title: Papilio aegeus aegeus
items.content_text: Feeding in Senecio minimus.

items.title: Papilio aegeus aegeus
items.content_text: Followed it for about 20 minutes and it never landed. Flying around Lemon Tree. This is the first female seen here. Male flew around last week.

items.title: Tisiphone abeona albifascia
items.content_text: Found in a sedge swamp flying around Lepidosperma laterale, feeding on Blackberry. Found after following up an old record designated 'Riddell' by George Lyell in 1920-30s. Not recorded here since. I found them last year but couldn't get photo until now.

items.title: Jalmenus icilius
items.content_text: First sighting of the season. On (and flying around) Acacia melanoxylon.

items.title: Papilio aegeus aegeus
items.content_text: Male seen every day since Nov 25. Seems to arrive at 10:30am and 4pm (ish) every day. Most of the time around the Lemon Tree but circles the house a few times too.

items.title: Papilio aegeus aegeus
items.content_text: Stayed overnight on the back door fly-wire, sheltering from the storm of that night. Flew about 10am next morning.

items.title: Papilio aegeus aegeus
items.content_text: Resting here in garden-planted Hakea laurina, then moved on to Lemon Tree.

items.title: Belenois java teutonia
items.content_text: Noticed for the first time this season, today. Many on a garden-planted Grevillea rosmarinifolia (which is their favourite in my garden each year). Virtually none seen last year - perhaps coinciding with locust spraying in north Vic.

items.title: Candalides hyacinthina hyacinthina
items.content_text: Two black spots on wing underside are a key feature. This was a pair flitting around and resting on leaves from dead fallen branch of Eucalyptus dives.

items.title: Vanessa kershawi
items.content_text: Three individuals (seemed small). Location approximate.

items.title: Lampides boeticus
items.content_text: New population emerged, after J.icilius disappeared 2+ weeks ago. Today I saw 12+ individuals throughout rail reserve. All had tails. Two individuals are pictured here. See also observation 2399.

items.title: Lampides boeticus
items.content_text: New population emerged, after J.icilius disappeared 2+ weeks ago. Today I saw 12+ individuals throughout rail reserve. This individual flew around & fed in Gorse. All had tails. See also observation 2400.

items.title: Trapezites lutea lutea
items.content_text: Resting on Dianella admixta and Kangaroo Grass. Using Kangaroo Grass as a vantage point for seeing other individuals and other species, all of whom it chased then returned to about the same spot. I saw 4-5 individuals flying around this area (about 20m).

items.title: Trapezites lutea lutea
items.content_text: Only one individual seen, feeding in Convolvulus arvensis. This is the first seen in this 'second flying' for this season. I looked for it on Feb 18 and Feb 11 and none were seen.

items.title: Trapezites lutea lutea
items.content_text: Numerous individuals seen flying, very flighty so difficult to photograph. The main pic here was the exception, resting on Haloragis heterophylla.
